{
  "texts": [
    "Specifically, LLMs use a deep neural network architecture called transformers that enable models to learn complex language patterns, capture long-range dependencies, and generate coherent responses [11].",
    "LLMs are the bedrock of two major NER paradigms: 1) pre-train and fine-tuning and 2) pre-train and prompt learning.",
    "We henceforth refer to these paradigms as fine-tuning and prompt learning, respectively.",
    "The former involves a two-step process where a language model is first trained on a massive amount of unlabeled text data and then fine-tuned on specific downstream NER tasks with labeled data.",
    "In contrast, prompt learning is a more recent paradigm that reformulates the NER task as textual prompts so that the model itself learns to predict the desired output in the second step.While fine-tuning LLMs has been shown to achieve strong performance on benchmark datasets [12], a major bottleneck is the development of large, annotated corpora."
  ]
}